        "additional_notes": "During the Identify Stakeholders process, especially in complex projects like internal system implementations, it is vital to uncover all stakeholders—even those not immediately visible or obvious. Stakeholders can range from direct users and sponsors to indirect parties affected by changes in processes, compliance, or technology.\n\nTo discover these \"hidden\" or less obvious stakeholders, project managers rely on various data gathering techniques. While reviewing organizational charts and project documents helps identify obvious stakeholders, more interactive techniques are essential to uncover others.\n\nAmong these, interviews and brainstorming sessions with key individuals and subject matter experts prove particularly effective. These techniques encourage open dialogue and knowledge sharing, revealing stakeholders who might otherwise be overlooked. Interviews allow the project manager to ask targeted questions and probe for information about roles, influences, and relationships within and outside the organization.\n\nAdditionally, stakeholder analysis workshops or facilitated group discussions can surface hidden stakeholders through collective input and cross-functional perspectives.\n\nBy employing such interactive and qualitative data gathering methods, the project manager gains a comprehensive understanding of the stakeholder landscape. This enables the development of more robust engagement strategies, ensuring all relevant parties are considered and effectively managed throughout the project lifecycle."
